= Containment Doctrine

The containment doctrine is the central external policy of Luminous: the uncontrolled leakage of technology is more dangerous than secrecy, isolation, or recognition. It is the reason Luminous withdraws from Earth rather than attempting to reform Earth through selective disclosure.

The doctrine is not based on the belief that Earth is uniquely immoral. It is based on the belief that existing Earth systems reward control, competition, secrecy, profit, and advantage. Technologies that can manufacture matter, generate abundant power, and transform computation would enter those systems as accelerants before law or society could adapt.

Containment applies to prototypes, technical processes, training, source material, and operational knowledge. It also applies socially. Residents are expected to understand that disclosure, even if casual, can be as dangerous as intentionally transferring technology or information.

The doctrine is controversial because it creates a moral cost. Luminous possesses capabilities that could relieve suffering, yet withholds them from general Earth deployment. Its defence is that premature release would not distribute abundance fairly; it would first empower whoever captured the technology fastest. Even if the immediate implementation would relieve a large portion of Earth's suffering, in the current shape of Earthen society, it would also create new forms of coercion, inequality, instability, and other general suffering. The containment doctrine therefore treats secrecy as a moral obligation rather than politically convenient.
